==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Draggle
<hw>Drag"gle</hw> <pr>(dr⟦acr⟧g"g'l)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Draggled</conjf>
<pr>(dr⟦acr⟧g"g'ld)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Draggling</conjf> <pr>(dr⟦acr⟧g"gl⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph>
<ety>[Freq. of <ets>drag</ets>. ⟦root⟧73. Cf. <er>Drawl</er>.]</ety>
<def>To wet and soil by dragging on the ground, mud, or wet grass; to
drabble; to trail.</def> <rj><au>Gray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With <qex>draggled</qex> nets down-hanging to the tide.</q>
<rj><qau>Trench.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Draggle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Draggle
<hw>Drag"gle</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be dragged on the ground; to
become wet or dirty by being dragged or trailed in the mud or wet
grass.</def> <rj><au>Hudibras.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>draggled</ent>⟦br⟧
